  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a vertical lift conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A vertical lift conveyor moves products straight up or down between elevations using platforms, carriages, or opposing belts in a true vertical path. Types include continuous vertical lifts (CVLs), C-frame elevators, Z-frame conveyors, VRCs, and spirals. They save 60-90% of floor space compared to incline conveyors.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            CVL vs. VRC , what is the difference?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>CVLs circulate multiple platforms continuously for high throughput (30-60+ UPM). VRCs shuttle a single platform up and down with stops at each level for lower throughput (5-15 cycles/min). CVLs cost more but handle higher volumes. VRCs are simpler, cheaper, and handle heavier loads including full pallets.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How much floor space does a vertical lift require?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Most packaging-line vertical lifts need 4x4 to 6x6 feet of floor space. A comparable incline conveyor needs 15-40 feet. Spirals need 5-10 feet in diameter. The vertical lift footprint stays constant regardless of elevation change height.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What products can vertical lifts handle?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Cases, cartons, totes, trays, bundles, and pallets. Products need a stable flat bottom. Weight ranges from 1 lb (small cartons on CVLs) to 6,000 lbs (pallets on heavy-duty VRCs). Loose, granular, or bulk products need <a href="/conveyor-types/flighted-scoop-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">flighted or scoop conveyors</a> instead.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

